Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

## Background and Motivation

Quite often, developers encounter the need to create an empty virtual method to allow derived classes to override it only if required.  But it is very uncomfortable and ugly looking.

## Proposed API

The proposal suggests extending the Roslyn API to allow the declaration of `void`/`Task` virtual methods without bodies.

Example:
```diff
public abstract class BaseClass
{
    public virtual void Setup()
    {
        // setup logic
        AdditionalSetup();
    }

-   protected virtual void AdditionalSetup() { }
+   protected virtual void AdditionalSetup();
}

public class DerivedClass : BaseClass
{
    public override void AdditionalSetup()
    {
        // additional setup logic
    }
}
```

Apologies if this should be in dotnet/runtime.  I wasn't sure if this belongs here or not as it relates more to the debugging experience?  Let me know if this should be filed elsewhere, or if more information is needed.

## Issue description

When attempting to step into a method which is decorated (or into a method within a class which is decorated) with an attribute such as `[DebuggerStepThrough]`, `[DebuggerNonUserCode]`, and `[DebuggerHidden]` (there may be other similar attributes but these are the ones I've tested with), I was expecting Visual Studio to step through that method and into the next available code not decorated with one of those attributes, but this did not occur.

For example, in the below code, if calling `classA.TestMethod()` I would expect it to step into `ClassC.TestMethod()`.

```csharp
    [DebuggerStepThrough]
    internal class ClassA
    {
        private ClassC ClassC { get; }

        public ClassA(ClassC classC)
        {
            ClassC = classC;
        }

        public void TestMethod()
        {
            ClassC.TestMethod();
        }
    }
```

From testing, it looks like if a property accessor (get or set) is invoked within a method being stepped-through, the debugger will not step beyond them into other code.  It seems like it may be something to do with the automatic step-over functionality (`Step over properties and operators (Managed only)`).  If that setting is unchecked then it steps in as expected, but it's obviously somewhat inconvenient to have that setting turned on all the time.

## Steps to Reproduce
The project that reproduces the issue can be found [here](https://github.com/Metritutus/DebuggerStepThroughTest001).

1) Place a breakpoint on line 12 in `Program.cs`.
2) Run the project.
3) When the breakpoint on line 12 is hit, attempt to step into the method.
4) The code steps over the method instead, onto line 13.
5) Attempting to step into the method on line 13 demonstrates the desired behaviour.

### Expected Behavior
When stepping into `classA.TestMethod()`, the code steps through to `TestMethod()` in `ClassC`.

### Actual Behavior
The code steps straight over `classA.TestMethod()` and on to the next line.

## Additional information
**OS version**: Windows 11 Version 22H2 (OS Build 22621.1555)
**Visual Studio version**: 17.6.1

## Update

I've discovered that it's not specific to an instance method being called on a property or anything like that.  It's if a property is accessed _at all_ from within a class or method decorated with `[DebuggerStepThrough]`, etc.

For example, this won't step into `TestMethod2()` unless the line accessing the property `ClassC` is commented-out/removed:

```csharp
    internal class ClassD
    {
        private ClassC ClassC
        {
            [DebuggerHidden] // Skips the "Your step-into request resulted in an automatic step-over" notification window.
                             // Doesn't have any bearing on the issue.
            get;
        }

        public ClassD(ClassC classC)
        {
            ClassC = classC;
        }

        [DebuggerStepThrough]
        public void TestMethod()
        {
            var classC = ClassC; // Commenting-out this line will allow the code to step into TestMethod2().
            TestMethod2();
        }

        public void TestMethod2()
        {
            string whatever = "";
        }
    }
```

I've updated the case to try and make this more clear.

